    "discriminators": [
     "The most distinctive vehicle in the taxonomy, and it is pure physics. A main rotor turns at roughly 5 revolutions per second with 2-5 blades, so BLADE-PASS lands at about 10-20 events per second — slow enough that both the ear and an onset detector resolve them as DISCRETE, LOW-FREQUENCY THUMPS rather than a pitch. Hence a very high onset_periodicity (~0.78, gated >= 0.35), an onset_rate_per_second in the 5-20 band, and dominant low_band_energy (gated >= 0.20). Nothing else in AIRCRAFT does this, and it is genuinely signal_separable.",
     "Against AIRCRAFT-JET: a jet is broadband roaring noise with NO periodic blade thump whatsoever. The onset_periodicity axis alone separates them — this subcategory's floor of 0.35 and JET's ceiling of 0.55 do not meet in practice.",
     "Against AIRCRAFT-PROP: the SAME blade-pass mechanism an order of magnitude faster. A propeller at ~40 rev/s with 2-3 blades puts blade-pass at 80-120 Hz, above the ~20 Hz limit of event resolution, so it FUSES into a pitched buzz — sustained_tonal with a measurable pitch_hz. The onset_rate_per_second axis is therefore the discriminator: ~12 discrete thumps per second here, versus a pitch there.",
     "Against AIRCRAFT-RADIO CONTROLLED: an RC quadcopter's small, fast rotors push blade-pass into the hundreds of hertz with an HF-tilted spectrum. It whines; it does not thump. The low_band_energy gate usually rejects it outright."
    ],
    "confusable_with": [
     "AEROProp",
     "AEROJet",
     "AERORadio",
     "AEROMil",
     "AEROMisc"
    ]
